by Walkerfort » Tue Apr 09, 2019 12:02 am

Sao Cervantes was officially granted its independence in 1962 from the British West Indies. For the first decade of independence, the economy grew an average 6% per year, with the government led by consecutive Labour governments. Despite the growing prosperity, a general sense of inequality pervaded in Black and Creole communities. Many claimed the Labour government had betrayed their own people for money. Distrust in the nation’s labor organizations in these groups rose, and voting populations sank to historically low levels. The final nail to the coffin would be the worldwide economic collapse of 1970, which dealt a harsh blow to the economy.

Rising from where the Cervantesian Labour Party had fallen was the Sao Cervantes Party, with a base of of blacks, creoles, hardcore nationalists, and many who had previously support trade unionism. Leading the Party was a charismatic individual named Leon Paleologos. He argued that the only way Sao Cervantes could define its own destiny was to leave the British Commonwealth of Nations, and spoke out against foreign domination of the economy, and condemned the unions that had sold out the country to foreign powers, especially the United States.

The President of Sao Cervantes is a popularly elected head of state with five-year terms. The President has many of the traditional roles in semi-presidential republics, such as appointing the head of government (Prime Minister) and other ministerial positions; dismissing the Prime Minister and dissolving the legislature; and declaring a state of war. As far as I can tell, the President is not subject to term limits. The incumbent President is José Joaquim Álvarez Vargas.
